column101: Use and become comfortable with each substance individually. Then go for it! There are many beneficial combinations, especially mdma. Cocaine has its value but should me mixed moderately and is better in recreational settings, I find it negates some positive benefits of mushrooms, specifically cocaine reinforces ego patterns while mushrooms dissolve them. Mdma and mushrooms are a match made in heaven and can have huge therapeutic benefit when mixed. Weed is no big deal if that’s something you already enjoy. Alcohol is the worst combo I know of (with any drug) and I recommend avoiding it. Tobacco is the first medicine and should be highly respected. It’s the oldest way to pray that I know of and if used ceremonially it can be a powerful grounding medicine for intention setting. But if you just smoke cigarettes then whatever, go for it. If you have a disfunctional relationship with any of these other substances, mushrooms will illuminate and make you aware of that. Ketamine is fun to throw into the mix when partying but will override most other drugs for its short duration of effect. It is better as a stand-alone in most cases. I have very limited experience with suppressants so can’t speak too much on that but the sedative effects could alleviate feelings of anxiety and physical discomfort. Other psychedelics are really fun to mix with psilocybin but I would  only recommend that for skilled and experienced psychonauts. Most of these combinations should only be attempted after becoming well experienced with them individually.
column130: It really all depends. There’s set, setting AND skill set to consider. Greater skill and experience mean you can loosen your guidelines as your comfort zone expands. I would get sleep, fast, and prepare myself more for a deep solo or spiritual high dose trip but wouldn’t give it much thought for lower doses. It all comes down to experience.

It is my personal belief, based on some evidence, that the neuroplasticity granted by the psilocybin allows change to come more easily. This is why I see psilocybin as a tool. column77: I microdose for 1 week whenever I find myself entering a depressive episode, to illeviate symptoms. We both have C-PTSD that affects our ability to stay in a good headspace during physical intimacy, these issues disappear completely while on psilocybin which allows us to renew our bond through intimacy to be closer and happier,  and the effect lasts for a month or two (allowing continued intimacy while sober - unobstucted by our C-PTSD) before we need to "reset" again. column50: Prepare your room to be as comfortable as possible. Have a puke bucket just in case, lots of water and snacks, a good queue of shows, nice ambient lighting, etc. Whatever makes you comfortable and relaxed. Prepare for a long trip, most doses take 4-8 hours to process. Be in a calm and happy state of mind. Whatever mindset you're in at the start, is how you'll likely feel during. column50: I would suggest achieving a comfortable set and setting understanding any environmental factors that effect emotion - anxiety, comfort, warmth, humidity, vibe of a room.. the “set and setting” be carefully setup. New psychedelic users may not be able to recognize potential triggers like the buzzing of a fridge or barking of a dog outside, so I would try to encourage them to create a ritualistic environment, start ceremonially with tea, put on Planet Earth, warm lights, be showered clean and comfortable, nourished. Set up multiple spaces each with their own positive energy so that if one gets emotionally burned for one reason or another, they can move to another pre-configured space that already has calming music etc playing. And remove potential hazards and maybe have a good trip sitter who is able and willing to mostly stay quiet for the duration.
column67: Consuming mushrooms with psilocybin dissolved into tea (low ish temperature hot water, not boil but bubbling a little to not burn psilocybin) was great and greatly reduced total trip time but made dosage wildly differ from dried mushrooms as the same amount of actual psilocybin hit/absorbed faster. So same dose would be more powerful but less long lasting.
column75: Concentrations vastly differ in caps/stems and batches. Part of in my mind the danger of tripping is the tendency - for my circles at least when we really got into it - would be to get a batch, whether a sheet of lsd or a batch of mushrooms, pragmatically you learn the strength and whether it’s good shit or what. Anyways the danger is having lots around as a result and starting to spontaneously trip, in retrospect unplanned trips were always the bad ones - orchestrated, planned trips were always much better. The other problem is that we would do them often and become deluded in various ways with frequent tripping, like deciding to quit our jobs and make soap in the woods because nothing matters anyways and we were seeing past the illusion of society. When the delusions last beyond the trips, it’s too frequent, and that all would happen because we’d get too “into it” and have large batches to get consistent doses. Anyways I’ll save that for a more appropriate question.
column76: I do not plan to consume psilocybin in the coming year
column77: I used psilocybin because I saw myself as an explorer of sorts. Curiosity - but then it became a self feeding cycle in a sense because I started to become delusional in some ways. In other ways, because it was fun. At other times, I believed I could completely change who I was as a person in a single trip, and though i felt that was true to an extent, it was in retrospect a sensation more than a reality, and in retrospect there were other underlying issues that tripping allowed me to hide from. I idolized hunter s thompson / fear and loathing, the tibetan book of the dead and wanted to experience the type of trips that explain “the light at the end if the tunnel”, a lot of curiosity, some misguided attempts at fixing mental illness (which i eventually realized was being exacerbated by my usage).
column88: Just that I don’t anymore and am completely sober after going through everything from psilocybin usage (by itself in periods of my lice) to LSD to DMT to hawaiian baby woodrose seeds (LSA)… I was tripping in various forms for a period 4-8 years ago and I am able to clearly reflect being removed from it. I will say the erowid vault is something I always referenced, along with the wiki.tripsit.me/wiki/drug_combinations safe drug combinations chart and would encourage widespread knowledge of each for the purposes of harm reduction. Erowid is the original though and has always had dosages and information correct.
column91: I would recommend reading the Erowid.org page on mushrooms including dosage, etc. but I would also offer a lot of advice as far as controlling setting, encouraging lower doses in general for the best experiences, and stressing the importance of set and setting and creating a comfortable environment that, should you find yourself upside down on the backside of a couch, your not going to hurt. Setting up rooms so that a toddler could be left alone without injuring, being comfortable etc and just try to express the importance of environmental triggers.
column101: It depends on the person. Nicotine is horrible for one person who doesn’t smoke but, if someone is having a craving while tripping, they should probably consume nicotine. Same for weed. At times it’s been like a light switch that has made a trip great, but, weed also makes some people paranoid, and for that person that is not a good thing. Generally I would consult the tripsit drug combinations chart as the golden rule for physical danger however beyond that it’s about the person remaining comfortable. Alcohol however in my experience has always significantly degraded the potency of hallucinogens. At some point I did really enjoy starting to drink post trip peak and being drunk by the “groovy” phase of a trip. The one time I did LSD after a cocaine bender though it actually was a fine trip, weirdly in that instance had I not had to work the next day it would have been fine. I did have strong confidence (a neighbour banged on my friends door and asked us to move our car while peaking, I confidently told the angry neighbours in a hunter s voice, “what do you mean we cant park here this is a sunday!”. Wouldn’t recommend mixing, beyond weed or whatever drugs someone needs to maintain their own baseline.
column130: All on point except for waiting an hour to take more. Every time I’ve ever tried to re-up my dose of any psychedelics it’s never really been powerful, like im de sensitized to the increased dose. Also its a terrible idea taking more mushrooms because you have to go through the initial nausea again but while actively tripping. Don’t take more just know your dose for next time.
column136: Regarding waiting a few days between trips. I think it’s important to space trips out a lot more than a few days and not for tolerance but because of losing a grip on reality. Like I said earlier, tripping too often made us all think we should give up our dreams and go make soap in the woods because we were seeing through the illusion the man was putting us on. This is sort of an example (well not really, it was reality) but it’s important to probably space them out and keep hallucinating as a “special” thing rather than a frequent thing, as we all became very deluded as far as how good it was for us and it took a lot of time in retrospect to realize the extent our psychological state was being effected. I don’t think I had a clear sober perspective on psychedelics until 3-6 months after cessation of use altogether in retrospect. Weekly tripping has a cumulative delusional effect that’s important to recognize.
column137: Away from sober people, creepy people, anything scary etc. my idiot friend went to a halloween haunt on LSD and got chased by a chainsaw dude. That’s the worst possible thing to do. Nature, away from people or potential sources of consequence, or in an area where you are in absolute control and will not be bothered.
column174: I am and have been sober for 4 years from all substances I ever abused, but long before quitting alcohol I quit psilocybin which had a drastically positive effect on my mental state. I don’t use it because I’ve learned everything I need to from my experiences and frankly can bring myself to the mental states I want to while sober through meditation, endorphin highs, etc - I can experience the joys I experienced hallucinating whole retaining control. My mental health is better than it ever has been abstaining from substance abuse, and, though people portray psilocybin as a miracle drug that is only a good thing and makes everyone a better person and cures depression etc etc - people only talk about the positives, without acknowledging that it can be very very damaging to ones mental health. The delusion of being under the spell of mushrooms while regularly tripping made this impossible to see - like a sick person determined to share their germs, the virus convinces the person to spread - the mushrooms convince the host that it’s only good. I had great experiences no doubt, but over time there was a net negative on my mental health.

column137: If it is cold, I like to find somewhere secluded in nature where I can make a fire and I won't be bothered by anyone. Tripping in heavily forested areas, or especially while on hikes in the mountains can add to the euphoric experience. A moderate dosage should be used on hikes, however. In warmer times/locations, I find the beach to also be especially enjoyable. The less family oriented, clothing optional beaches are best, as one can easily find like-minded people to socialize with, or if it's a secluded beach, some minds will enjoy the solitude.   In society, we are given the impression that humans are beings evolved to be at a level greater than nature, who can abuse and control nature to our benefit, and using these mind-altering drugs while in areas that are less disturbed by humans can draw us closer to our source. Users that are unwilling to leave home, possibly due to the weather, can also have a more familiar, less explorative trip at home, where they can use any amenities that are available to them there that may enhance their experience. Overall, I think there are very few places that a person could have a bad trip at. As long as they are free to move around as they wish, are not in a hazardous area, and are in a well lit area or in a dark area with a means of light, a variably good experience can be had just about anywhere, but it is up to the user to find their sweet spot.

column50: For dried mushrooms : take 1g at most your first time, and take it in two separate doses of 0.5g. Wait at least two hours before the second dose, and make sure you’re feeling okay. Don’t do it alone. Have at least one trusted friend with you, and at least one person who will remain sober to take care of you if something goes wrong. Try to be outside during the trip. Don’t mix the mushrooms with lemon juice. Don’t consume them with an empty stomach, or a full stomach. Have a light meal 2 hours before. If you’re seeing visuals, try not to look at yourself in the mirror, it may trip you out. Above all, don’t worry too much. It’s one of the safest drugs out there.

column67: Microdoses helped me a lot with my mental health, I felt more awake and felt really well rested and healthy, it also helped a lot with my Obsessive Compulsive Disorder.  When I had light doses I experience deep thoughts of the world and I feel as though I unlocked many interests that I never thought I would've had. It definetly helped me the most with taking in life through a different lense and opened my mind to different perceptions.  Strong doses was very touchy, sometimes I had amazing experiences where I really looked at the world we lived in and I think for the first time truly appreciated it. Other times I spun out of control and felt like I was dying or sometimes even thought the trip would never end for the rest of my life. But even in those bad experiences I have felt there was a lot of good that came out of it. I still fear of dying but it's a different type of fear, an indirect one. Instead of fearing where I will go when I die, I seem to worry more about how it would affect my loved ones and how their lives would be after.
column75: I used to not own a scale so I would usually just guess on how much to take and I would also sometimes take it on an empty stomach which really affects the strength and duration of your trip. Since it's all the same strength for 1 large batch you can dial in how much you like by increasing your doses from 0.1 grams and just keep adding 0.1 until you are happy with the dose you take.

column136: I don’t really believe in “bad trips” the way they’re currently framed - as if the mushrooms themselves are bad for you. So whether or not you have a “bad trip” or a healing one can really be up to you…but you need confidence and a strong sense of self for it to work that way. Personal insecurities without mental/emotional preparation or readiness to confront them may result in you having a bad time, but the mushrooms aren’t to blame for that.

column67: after ~4g, time and reality warp and blend. i spent a day eating mushrooms lying in bed, some 9-12g total, and saw myself die in a million different ways, but always being reborn. the anxiety and paranoia was intense but so was the relief, and i was in a place where i wanted to be dead so the trip was a welcome break from suicidality, and watching the deaths was cathartic, like i could say "see, that's me, dying" and it helped stave off the ideation. i would NEVER recommend this method to anyone, you can develop serotonin syndrome, have a complete psychotic break, lose a sense of reality permanently, burn your receptors forever, etc etc but it was what i needed.  lower doses up to about 4/5g are immense and overwhelming but enjoyable if you've framed them correctly (goals/intent/curiosity/self guided meditation) doses between 1-3.5g are my preferred method of tripping as they are more manageable and i can even interact briefly with other people during.

column136: Trips, or "hero doses" are insane. 2 grams is a heavy trip on its own. It's enough to unlock the secrets of the universe while becoming one with it. This kind of trip, I highly recommend doing it outdoors and at a hot spring on a beautifully hot summer day. Be out with nature and fly. It is a good idea to take an extra day off afterwards to ponder one's revelations as they may live vividly for quite some time afterwards but it isn't necessary. column39: I recommend online retailers, they are easy to source and reliable. I know many people will have trepidations about the legality, and also the reputability of online drug vendors, and anybody looking to purchase should be fully aware that sale of psilocybin is in fact not legal at the moment, and make decisions based on their feelings towards that. However, I can say with conviction that I do not believe anybody will be prosecuted for purchasing recreational amounts of psilocybin on the internet. First of all, law enforcement will simply not waste their efforts on a small offences like this, as those efforts are usually invested towards the traffickers and retailers. The Canadian government has overwhelmingly taken a non-punishing stance towards drug users in recent years, with many efforts to decriminalize illicit substances to some degree. Secondly, psilocybin is in a cultural position similar to that which marijuana was shortly before being legalized, in that as our cultural stance towards these substances changes and policies to legalize them are being drafted, the black market has become less of a priority for law enforcement. In regards to the reputability of online vendors, certainly everybody should take the necessary precautions when purchasing mind altering substances, however many of the retail sites have accessible customer reviews and I have never had a poor experience when I have done my due diligence. Also, psilocybin in its whole dried fork is very easily identifiable and difficult to 'spike' with another drug or otherwise conceal, so you do not need to worry about being dosed with something unfamiliar and potentially dangerous. If you still feel unsure purchasing drugs on an online website, then I would suggest talking to your friends.

column75: Make sure you have a scale that can read grams and small measurements, and you will be okay with dosing. As for which dose to take, I recommend doing research and feeling what you would be comfortable with. It's always a good idea to start slow and build up. That said, the one challenge I do face sometimes is honestly, under-dosing. I often become anxious and lower my intended dose, which can lead to me feeling underwhelmed or even disappointed. While the psychedelic experience is naturally a little intimidating, you need to have courage in yourself and you will be rewarded for that, and your mind is more capable of handling things than you realize sometimes. As long as you have done proper preparation in terms of set & setting, I believe it's best to commit to the dose you have decided on.
column77: There are a multitude of reasons, I will try to summarize some as best I can. First of all, I have found psilocybin instrumental to understanding myself and exploring my traumas and other issues in a positive manner. I struggle to suggest psilocybin as a 'cure' for any mental illnesses or anything, and it is no substitute for therapy and other methods, but I can say that I have much more clarity in my life, and have found better coping mechanisms for stresses & anxieties. In this sense, it can give you perspective on your life that can be hard to see at other times, almost like a 3rd party observer. Which brings me to the next thing, I find a lot of peace in the feeling of ego-dissolution. I'm our daily lives we get so wrapped up in performing the social role we are supposed to, and we can become so driven by our egos, that to step away from your 'self' at times is quite a cathartic experience, like taking off your suit at the end of a long day at work. It is a weightless feeling to step out of You, to be free from all the little stresses that come with having an identity and a role in society, and for just a fleeting time, to have a raw, unfiltered experience with reality, free from the biases and perceptions of your Self. When you have accumulated a certain amount of pressure in your life, this can be a very cathartic experience. In essence, this present-ness and loss of ego is a goal in many spiritual practices, but it can be very difficult to align that mindset with the realities of the modern world, and so to have that ability to 'escape' at times can be very precious. Finally, I have found it to make me more empathetic, less selfish, and generally an improved character. My relationships have improved and I feel more love for people, and less desire to engage in tribalistic or hierarchical behaviour. I also feel more in tune with nature, and all of this I consider very positive and believe psilocybin has been instrumental in this, and in developing a more nuanced and congruent model of the world. Although once again I do not consider it the sole factor in any of this, but simply a great tool.
column88: Again, it is an incredibly complex situation. Another reason I could say I use it is simply for the ecstasy, it feels fantastic physically and gives me an electric sense of energy. Some would reduce this to a hedonistic use of mushrooms, but I believe it is therapeutic to let yourself give in to emotions like these and experience a childlike joy and wonder at times. Or conversely, to let yourself feel the depths of your suffering on a particularly emotional trip, and to come back from it stronger. Not every mushroom trip is the same, nor taken for the same reason. At times I take them because I want to understand something about myself, and other times it is just to chase an excitement. Broadly speaking, I would say it's a form of self-therapy, but like therapy, it cannot solve any problems alone and requires you to put in effort outside of sessions. But primarily between the feelings of ego-loss and the physical euphoria, psilocybin provides a unique perspective on life that has helped me to grow and find some grounding in a very chaotic world.
column91: There is plenty of information available online, and I think simply doing research is the best way to inform yourself. column101: I would advise against it personally, I think a mushroom trip can and should stand on its own. I especially advise against the use of cannabis, which you may think is a good pairing, but to me it exacerbates the anxiety of a trip and can take away from the experience. Some people may enjoy it, but at the very least I would make sure you are very comfortable with the effects of mushrooms before mixing with cannabis, and do not do so if you are new to either substance. In regards to alcohol, I think this depends on your dose and comfort level with both substances, i.e. if you can handle a beer or two without getting tipsy, I think you will be okay. But I cannot see getting drunk on psilocybin to be enjoyable. As for other substances, it's always a personal choice, I think you just need to be comfortable with both substances and make sure you do enough research to know the combination is not dangerous.
column130: Certainly, as I know my answers may not be typical. First of all, I do not feel a trip sitter is necessary and may in fact be detrimental to your experience. There is very little risk of somebody harming themselves on psilocybin given that they have chosen a safe setting, and as psilocybin is a deeply inward experience, it can exaggerate social anxiety, especially if the other person is sober to highlight your different mental state. You may become too preoccupied with this or anxious to fully enjoy your trip. For your first trip, I strongly recommend being alone for this reason. However, ultimately it does depend on your comfort level, I would become familiar with the effects before taking it in the presence of others, or if you really don't want to be alone, at least find somebody close to you who is willing to trip together. Also psilocybin is not a socially conducive drug nor is it likely to make you manic, and most likely you will want to lie down alone anyway. Of course your ideal setting is going to depend on who you are and what you're trying to achieve, but I would suggest a safe indoor trip before experimenting further. The outdoors for example can be a great setting for psilocybin, but you do not want to get a flare of anxiety in a public space. So, I tend to start my trip in an indoor setting where I can transition to outdoors partway through a trip, and I strongly suggest this to anyone who is able. Otherwise just make sure you are in a comfortable space, private if you prefer it to be, and know what to expect. I have limited success in places with crowds, namely a public beach and an art gallery, but I would only recommend this to somebody experienced and with careful dosage. In terms of mindset - many people recommend not to take psychedelics in a bad or depressed mood. I think this also depends on your comfort level, if you have some experience for me taking mushrooms can be very positive and fruitful when I am having a poor experience in life, as it gives you a fresh perspective and can be emotionally cathartic. But you need to be careful of a few things, one is to go into it with the right intent, because you need to be prepared to face your issues and process the uncomfortable emotions that come with this. If you are not yet experienced with psilocybin or have poor emotional regulation, then you should absolutely wait to take them in a more positive mood. You should however, always try to have a positive attitude towards the mushrooms themselves, even when your mood is low - if you think you're going to have a bad trip, you probably will. There are some head spaces I would suggest avoiding using psilocybin as well, namely if you are concerned about an upcoming deadline or will weigh on you, and if you have any fear of getting caught (that could mean your parents walking in you, or not being prepared to face crowds in public) as the anxiety of this will spoil the trip. For planning, the trip will last about 6-8 hours and in my experience has little hangover. You really only need to set about half a day aside for the trip which makes it very convenient. I think the best times to take it are almost immediately after waking up and planning to relax the rest of the day, or on the evening with enough time for an hour or two of reflection before bed. The latter way you can get some things done during the day. The next day, you may have a headache but should otherwise feel fine.   Finally, I just want to quote Dale Pendell, where he describes the ideal setting for psilocybin.- "Indoors, at night, in a circle. Outdoors, in the forest, wandering. In the desert. On the prairie. In Madrid. In London. In Germany. In Florida, at a Grateful Dead show, in tie-dye. Alone, when you must speak with the spirit yourself, one on one." Of course this is a poetic description and maybe not practical, but it does speak to the fact that psilocybin is a highly versatile substance which will give you fresh and interesting perspectives in a variety of settings, should you seek them out. Of course, due diligence and planning are important, but I also do believe the perfect set & setting may spring itself on you spontaneously, and if you are so inclined, you should be prepared to take it.
column136: In regards to music, I just want to say I think it's important to trust your judgement here. I know MAPS has a fairly strict view towards music on a trip, I believe it should be more flexible. The thing to keep in mind is that music will highly exaggerate your emotions and can often set the tone of the trip. So, depending on your mindset at different moments, it is possible for certain music to give you anxiety. Rather than using a playlist, I simply keep my phone on me so I can change music or turn it off as I wish. Music can really shape the feeling of a trip, so you may want to experiment without using it at all, and another trip where you really focus on it. And don't be afraid to dance! It feels amazing. Energetic music is electrifying on psilocybin.   In addition to journaling, you should make reading a part of your post-trip routine. You need to integrate the feelings, and thankfully many have tread where you have. You can look for books by drug users like Terence Mckenna, but you will also find ideas that help you understand in unlikely places, like philosophy or spirituality. This isn't to say that psilocybin will make you some esoteric religious nutcase, but it can open you up to a complex range of feelings that you will need a broad perspective to truly understand, should you wish to. For others, it is largely about the sensory experience, but it is unlikely you will have many trips without confronting some challenging feelings. Community forums are also a great place to look for ideas. Read, read, read is my advice.   Bad trips are rare and being afraid of them will only make it more likely to happen to you. You only need to look online to see how there are so many more positive experiences with psilocybin than negative ones. If you do find yourself in a bad headspace, lie down, be comfortable, either alone or with somebody very close to you, and turn off any distractions. Just allow yourself to push through it, psilocybin trips are brief, and the risk of any lasting effect on your mood is incredibly low. You will be back to your normal self in just a couple hours, and you need to remind yourself of that. The beginning of a trip is often when anxiety spikes as you transition into the head space, and reminding yourself that it's temporary during this stage can help a lot. Once you pass that initial hump, there is very little risk of falling into a bad place.   If you are somebody who would still worry about this stuff, there are plenty of peer reviewed studies on psilocybin with overwhelmingly positive results and I encourage everyone to look at these for reassurance. The only serious identified risk factor to keep in mind is a genetic history of schizophrenia.
column137: I have already touched on this in an answer, so I will keep this one brief lol. I think indoors at home is the best environment. If you live with parents or a roommate however, you will want to do this on a day you are sure you won't run into them, unless you are comfortable with them knowing what you're doing. You want somewhere you can be comfortable, relaxed, familiar. Your bedroom is perfect. If you are able to transition to an outdoor space, this would be ideal.   Other locations would be outdoors, in a private space, such as a campsite. You can also look for places that present a unique sensory experience, for example the beach can be wonderful if you're comfortable swimming on psilocybin. Other examples would be gardens, art installations, or a meadow. Basically anywhere you feel comfortable, have space, and presents an interesting sensory appeal or physical activity. Psilocybin makes you feel alive in a very raw sense, so doing ordinary things like swimming, smelling flowers, or lying in the shade of a tree all take on a very different and visceral appeal. One thing I really believe is you should have unique trips. If you trip in the same location every time, it will become monotonous and hard to gain anything new. So, start at home, but once you have experience try some new things like this.   But dosage is important to setting too - outdoors you may want to take small-medium doses to maintain your wits and engage with the environment, on a large dose you will be more inclined to stay in bed at home exploring inner space. So choose your dose according to your setting. There are sensory trips, and inwards trips. s

column75: Also, if you're microdosing, you can blend up the shrooms and put them into .5g or 1g gel caps.  This makes microdosing extremely easy. column50: Talk to someone you know and trust who has done mushrooms - ask them about what they experience, what they would recommend for you, and/or if they are willing to join your trip or participate as a sober companion. Do them with one or a few friends, but not strangers. Eat well beforehand, drink plenty of water, and choose a comfortable, safe place. Weigh your dosage and start small to test the waters. column77: I was initially intrigued by psilocybin as a way to unlock new dimensions of reality, expand my thought process/consciousness, and experience a new altered state. Since my initial trip, I have learned psilocybin is useful as a therapeutic tool, a medium to connect with the shared energy of the universe, and a tool for self-improvement. The innate ego-death of psilocybin trips has allowed me to say things I couldn't while sober or even to a therapist. It has allowed me to step outside the physical boundaries of my body and self and appreciate life as a shared, conscious energy, and view those around me as not separate from myself but part of a multi-faceted lifeform. These revelations, and others, have helped me grow as a person mentally, and spiritually, like a larvae shedding realities in order to evolve into a new version of itself.
column87: To feel like a raw, unfiltered version of my consciousness
column88: I have been using psilocybin in varying doses and for varying uses for 8 years - I am enamoured and drawn to the expansion of my consciousness beyond my own body, and the experience in living in nothing but the present moment. In western society, these states can be hard to reach in daily life. But I recently heard Dr. Jill Bolte Taylor, a harvard-trained neuroanatomist on the 10% Happier Podcast, where she explained her theory on whole brain living, being that we each have four 'personalities' inside our head: 2 in the right hemisphere, and 2 in the left. #1 on the left is the CEO with the to-do list, the executive functioner. #2 on the left is the emotional centre, the part of us that hurts, lashes out, always looking for the negatives or the evolutionary risks and threats. #3 on the right is our emotional experiential self, thrilled to be in the present moment and joyfully curious. #4 on the right side can be thought of as pure consciousness, feeling connected to the universe without the boundaries of individualism and physical limitations. It's been my experience that psilocybin and other psychedelics seem to tap into this part of the brain in extraordinary ways, and this possible connection is incredibly intriguing to me, and I hope this concept is explored in future research on the effects of psilocybin and other psychedelics on the brain!
column91: Ask a friend or a trusted individual you know has had experience. Be cautious when doing research online, as information can range from extremely positive to extremely negative. However, it is important to keep an open mind and consider any risks that may apply to you. Once you feel comfortable with the idea of using psilocybin safely, you can progress to next steps.
column101: Use caution and intuition when considering mixing substances. Don't mix two or more substances you've never used, and be similarly prepared for using psilocybin as any another substance. Ensure you consider any safety concerns for each substance, and ensure you're in a safe, comfortable environment with safe, comfortable people.
column130: Environmental recommendations and guidelines can change depending on experience and comfort levels with psilocybin. I would not recommend taking mushrooms for the first time at a concert or other busy environment with lots of people or hazards, but a small or medium dose for experienced users in the same environment isn't a concern.
column136: Although it may be tempting to reap the benefits of psilocybin on a regular basis, long breaks of weeks to months maximize each experience, while frequent trips diminish the positive effects.
column137: I consume psilocybin in a variety of environments. My apartment or the homes of friends or family, outdoors while camping or travelling, and for events like parties or shows. Good environmental characteristics include: a place you're comfortable, a familiar place, a place you can remain for long periods of time, a place with access to water, food, bathroom, and emergency help if needed, a place with similar energy (i.e. don't go to the courthouse/elementary school on drugs), a place with low risk of police or enforcement presence, and most importantly a place that facilitates the goals of your trip, whether that be self-reflection, human connection, relaxation, etc.

column67: Quality/potency an be a HUGE variable.  My most intense experience was an unknown quantity but probably only about 2 - 2.5 grams of very blue bruised mushrooms (possibly relevant, possibly not) and it was a VERY intense experience with a peak of about 1 - 1.5 hours that was very difficult (auditory hallucinations, confusion, panic, inability to comprehend what was happening, etc.).  I would've figured it was like a 4+ gram dose if I had to guess but there's just no way I ate that much, it couldn't have been more than 2 and a bit.  And likewise I've also recently consumed about 2 - 2.5 grams of very poor mushrooms and didn't feel much at all.  A supply of safe, tested, measured, quantified dosages is desperately needed so people don't end up with unintentional overdoses (which, while almost never fatal or health-damaging, still aren't usually a ton of fun).
column75: This time it's been the slow process of discovering that the mushrooms I obtained were of low potency (ie. took what I thought was the ideal amount, it was underwhelming; next time took more, still underwhelming; next time took more, still underwhelming...).  Ideally, don't get crappy low potency mushrooms that are going to mess with your established concept of doses.  *sigh*

column101: No, but I'd sure like to find out, once and for all, what the interplay is with SSRI/SNRI's.  Some accounts say they mute the efficacy of psilocybin, others say they don't.  Well which is it, scientists?!?  In my experience and from other anecdotal info, yes, these anti-depressants DO have a muting effect on psilocybin. column130: Regarding the adulthood question:  On one hand it's best if you can wait until your brain is as close to being fully developed as possible before experimenting with psychedelics, but on the other hand, teenagehood can also be an excellent time for such growth.  And regarding the emergency services question...  Okay, sure, you should know how to get emergency medical support if it's absolutely necessary, but... you do NOT want to be tripping while detained in an ER/hospital/strapped to a gurney, etc!  The medical community at large is disturbingly oblivious to how to provide proper care and compassion for individuals experiencing heavy psychedelic experiences.  I know I'd infinitely rather have to get through a difficult trip on my own than in a hospital, which would be infinitely worse!  :-S

column324: The framing of your questions might be a little off in my case. You're looking for immediate, let's call them "medical" benefits for our purposes. In large part tryptamine psychedelics changed me over-all and for the better. Changes in the context of cognitive flexibility (I.e. permanent agnosticism [see Robert Anton Wilson] ) and spiritually in terms of seeing things as connected gradients not binaries in nature is now tattooed on me. See Terence McKenna's commentsry on "being a psychedelic person" . Anecdotal as it may be, it gives a good overall sense of ehat many of us experiened over the years. Now habitual thought patterns of the day to day prosaic realities sure that's a bit different. Breaking habits like cigarettes for example. Those things last for a bit and old patterns do return. As a result psilocybin is absolutely helpful in kickstarting the breaking of patterns. This must be followed by real work but getting a head start is a great thing too.

column324: As a writer and poet, I often experience creative breakthroughs (such as finding useful connections between two topics I might be interested in) while tripping which can lead to days or weeks of reflection and productivity. The additional emotional clarity and sensitivity to building abstract connections between disparate topics also remains for at least a week. Outside of creativity, I find that I am frequently more patient with myself, more forgiving of my own shortcomings, and more eager to find new routines going forward. As someone prone to psychosis, too much repeated use of moderate dose psilocybin in a short period can lead to increased paranoia, anxiety, and thought spirals, but this has never been the case with occasional use.

column324: Big question! I'll say this much because I think it's important. I usually journey alone and must admit that I do not practice integration as much as I ought to. For that reason, some of the benefits may not be maximal. Furthermore, journeying often opens me up emotionally (if that makes sense) and makes me, therefore, more vulnerable to negative events, triggers etc. in my life. Without a strong support and integration network, this has resulted more than once in me reacting more negatively to these events. Meaning,  emotional and psychological distress, depressive episodes and shutdowns. These are things that happen to me anyway, it's not CAUSED by journeying but has a few times been amplified by it. I hope that makes sense.   That being said and being very real, the overall impact of psychedelics has been very positive for me. And I now, in fact, have a bit of an integration network (not formal, but something...) and that has helped me to better cultivate the positive effects of my journeys.

I consumed my most recent "hero dose" over 13 months ago with the stated intention of discovering the source of my feelings of anxiety. During my "trip" I experienced strong feelings of fear, grief and sadness which were linked to events from my childhood. Note: I also experienced positive emotions, wonderous visions and enduring feelings of connection to all life. Exploring those negative events led me to seek therapeutic guidance which, in turn, led me to Internal Family Systems Therapy. IFS has allowed me to better understand my emotional reactions and has given me a framework for an ongoing self-led healing path.  More than 1 year following my "trip", I continue to have experiences in nature and connecting with other humans that bring child-like joy. When have negative experiences, I look at these as opportunities to grow and understand myself better. My "hero dose" set in motion a series of psychological shifts, healing work and exploring new interests that have endured over a significant period of time.

column324: The sessions I did using high dosages, above 2.5 grams have had permanent impact on how I approach life. It's the "ego-death" part of the session that brings out all this change, being able to see yourself and others without judgement is inexplicable. I began using mushrooms a lot at high doses in 2023. I had several 'bad trips' which equated to negative experiences while high on the mushroom. These experiences turned very severe so that by the end of the year, I had such horrendous schizophrenic psychosis induced by the mushroom, and before that paranoid psychosis, that my relationship with the mushroom has forever been changed. I am hesitant to take them again, the schizophrenic time loops are really awful and I hate being in psychosis.  I began experimenting with ketamine as well in 2023, and I now see it as a much more potentially beneficial psychedelic than mushrooms. I believe mushrooms is neither good or evil, but it does not give the grandiose knowledge people are claiming it to, it is something far more sinister to mankind. Sinister because it is natural, and we have to remember that all of Life is a competition amongst all the members of Life, including the mushroom.  So let's be real and accept the fact that all psychedelics may induce schizophrenia during the trip, and may affect those who consume it for the rest of their life, because the visions and thoughts may turn into beliefs about the nature of reality. Am I lucky or blessed to have seen past life and imagine that I witnessed the feeding of quantum worlds, Hindu deities, and demons? or cursed? Magical thinking, schizophrenic hallucinations, catatonia... these are all possible outcomes for days or even months or years afterwards... But you have to be strong and believe in your own mind and in the end, I always feel much better off, and grateful for the visions that aren't too painful to witness.  Must be noted that I have ingested psychedelics for a long time (20 years) and that one large dose doesn't just ruin a person. And I am not mentally impaired from these experiences... I do not suffer, and it has not affected my life negatively, only positively, but one must be willing to accept that your worldview might be changed by inducing these substances at great doses.

column324: I don’t actually like magic mushrooms. They make me wildly introspective. This last year I’ve warmed up a bit to them but I think I’m going to stop again. I have adhd and autism. I didn’t get the science and math autism, I got the substance abuse autism.   I’ve always wanted my brain to shutoff. It doesn’t matter what holistic approach I take, if my brain doesn’t quit, the drug is just escapism at best.     If you don’t do drugs or never done them, magic mushrooms are wonderful. I’m introspective and aware of myself and everything around me on an outrageous level. I don’t want to “feel” myself out more.   Magic mushrooms piss me off the first week because I’m emotionally disregulated for a week. Then it takes another week or so to feel like myself again. I’ve never used them medicinally so I don’t know what microdosing feels like.   Either way,  it’s a personal experience. It terms of what I want out of a drug. Mushrooms are a pass for me. I’d need to have something pretty specific I’m going after and even then, mushrooms wouldn’t be my first choice.   However, if you e never done drugs and are struggling or need a pick me up, I know these are life changing for people.
It has permanently changed my perspective on life and spirituality resulting in an ability to better see beyond self imposed limitations.

I have a learning disability and experience less cognitive fatigue and a better processing speed after consuming mushrooms. I can read and understand faster and have an easier time typing. My mood is also better. Both result in better productivity and quality of life.

column174: my use experience having gone through phases of microdose, macrodose, experimenting with different durations between trips, etc, has lead my to believe there are medium to long term effects of usage that negatively impact mental health through mechanisms varying from poor judgement, to delusion, to direct brain chemistry changed that are negative. I have avoided use in the past 12 months because I believe I have learned what there is for me to learn from psychedelics and tripping again serves no utility, with potentially devastating mental health consequences. Saturating myself with sleep diet and exersize and no drug/substance use of any family has lead me to achieve prolonged joy and happiness that far surpasses whatever I once felt under the immediate or after effects of psychedelics. In other words, absolute sobriety from psychedelics long term combined with therapy and exercise and good diet has been enlightening in the long term.

column324: I have noticed that things that are hidden in my subconscious will surface a few days after a hero or heavy dose. As an example last June I did a healing session. A few days later a revelation arose from my subconscious. I have been an extremely small busted woman all of my life. Fried egg small. I stopped realizing how much the ongoing jokes and downright rude comments hurt about the age of 20. I pushed it down so far. I became self- depreciating to the time that I made the jokes before anyone else could. I had become totally immune to the deep pain it caused.  This is what surfaced days after my healing session.  I cried buckets.  Spoke with my husband, doctor,  psychiatrist, and psychologist. By June I had my first consultation with my plastic surgeon and was booked for surgery and an appointment for surgery booked for October 12th. I got a call in July. They had a cancelation for July 25th and I took it. When I woke after surgery, I looked down and loudly exclaimed "I have boobs!", just as the nurse walked in. We both laughed. It changed my life completely.  I gained instant confidence.  It took me a couple weeks to realize what the exact difference was.  For the first time in my life I felt whole, complete. I was 57 at the time. I turned 58 earlier this month and still wonder at the difference.  I look at Mt body and marvel at my breasts. It may sound crazy to some but I have another 50 years to live. All the pain, all the hurt was gone. Just like that and for the first time in my life, I am confident in myself.

I would say that the major effect I've noticed is an increased flexibility in my thinking and ability to take in and synthesize new ideas. It helps me form connections and see patterns in information which has greatly increased my capacity to understand new knowledge. I have found this to be a permanent effect, although it does seem to peak in the weeks/months immediately following use. I find that during that period, I am very drawn to reading books and seeking out other sources of knowledge, and that I have very vivid clarity of understanding.   I would also note that it has hugely affected the way I listen to music and consume other forms of art, and that I have a much deeper appreciation of these things that has stuck well after using psilocybin. Although these feelings peak during a trip, I feel that my appreciation for music especially has been forever changed.   Other lingering effects include an increased sense of well-being, connection to others, and the breaking down of negative thought patterns and habits, however I find these effects short-lived compared to the others, and have often found myself slipping back into old habits in the weeks & months following use. They have also made me much more open to new experiences and changes in my life, although I find that this effect also diminishes over time as I find myself slipping into old comforts.

column339: A friend in the mental health research/alternative health field suggested I try this therapy. I proceeded to apply for a section 57 and once I obtained it, and after a preparation process that took one year that included abstinence from drugs and alcohol and anti depressant medication, I went to a private home and did it with a private guardian/therapist. The many professional mental workers who were offering the therapy wanted $2000 but the private guardian did it for free. I felt a slight sense of gimmick or snake oil salesmanship from the psychologists who were connected to the project. The private guardian seemed more genuine and authentic. My goals were to explore and repair my emotional landscape. To reduce depression and fear of death. To gain understanding of my path and find a way to cherish my life,  I had to appeal a few times to receive my section 57.
column342: My symptoms were sadness, sense of worthlessness and meaninglessness. What I liked about the session was that the place was comfortable and reassuring. The private guardian was a person I trusted and who knew me. That person had been on a long personal quest. I could relate to them. The place had cool paintings and textiles and an atmosphere that was spiritual to me. I felt cared for by family. Maybe linked to my personal mental challenges that I was appreciative of that aspect. The music was an essential part of the process, following the bright and dark places it was carrying me to. The very intriguing part of my experience during that session was that I had a question and answer with the ´plant’. I was able to see some irony and playfulness with the spirit of the medicine. There was a feeling of partnership. At times it felt like a trickster, it’s hard to explain. I felt I became the plant and was a seed underground. I was visited by strong male and female representations of support in my life, I connected with maternal lineage. I saw my mother who is deceased in a mountain and my grandmother as the snow. I spend a lot of time in the mountains and this made the connection of a notion of home and love in the external world to me. I could go on, The experience was profound yet incomplete, I have changed since starting the whole preparation and session. And post session integration.

column324: I've found that over the years the positive effects don't linger as long as when I first started using. I think partially because I am now more aware that I will "come back down" rather than when I was younger I would feel completely remade and thought it was my new reality. After a few years of focusing on integration, these ups and downs have certainly mellowed out. That's not to say that the experiences have become any less meaningful - maybe even a bit more so, because I feel much more able to access that state of mind on a day-to-day basis. In earlier trips, the lasting sense of connectedness would last several months, and slowly reduce to a few weeks to a few days to sometimes almost zero in times when I was struggling more to stay in the mentally connected place. It just feels like a different kind of learning, and I firmly believe I will experience those dramatic breakthroughs again at a different stage in my life

column415: My primary reasons are spiritual, for the purposes of experiencing awe and wonder and a heightening of meaning-making, religious ecstasy, things of this nature. Also as a professional artist, for artistic inspiration, and also at times as a social/shared experience with others. I used to view shrooms as a very solitary drug but increasingly find myself doing it mostly with other people, which might have more to do with when the opportunity naturally arises rather than as an intentional decision, though that change over the past decade feels significant to me.
column421: I have a history of psychosis which as I have grown has lessened significantly and now mostly arises in times of intense joy and excitement or intense fear and stress. column415: I  use psilocybin to make colours brighter and music better. Trees and nature is more interesting on psilocybin. Which results in an interesting hike in nature. I find music really sounds good, particularly electronic dance music.  It helps dissociate at socially anxious social events like at a DJ show. I enjoy more being in a crowd or walking around an outdoor music festival. At smaller social events, a micro dose of psilocybin helps reduce the amount of alcohol consumed and saves money. A microdose makes one feel drunk and wobbly and makes the lazer lights and bright rave outfits really pop out and be interesting to look at. Some art displayed at outdoor music festivals really look fascinating while on psilocybin.

If I had had no support system though, it likely would of been devastating to my life because it is very difficult to accept that you could miss that much of your life and not even know it's not there. I continued use after a gap and the therapy in a controlled manner and have since grown intellectually, emotionally, and spiritually, accepted myself and others around me for who they are and am greater able to remove myself from personal relationships that do not serve who I am and what I am working toward.

column421: A lot of these questions tell me you are asking a lot of wrong questions about how medicalized usage functions for people. Maybe that’s not the point, but a lot of these questions are WELL WEALTHY ABLED WELLNESS questions for elites that treat psilocybin as a cool new sweat lodge ayahausca fad. That is not how they are best used for people who actually need them to support their DISABLED WELLNESS. These two patterns are VERY distinct and the one your questions seem to prioritize are for the pattern of the former. The latter are the ones who need these studies to shift access, safety, and affordability to utilize psilocybin as a wellness tool in a complex regime of health management. I find this VERY concerning and not at all surprising. Hopefully you can divide this research into ACTUAL patients for whom this is a very useful tool, and the well wealthy and abled who use it as a way to go from already well and wealthy to more well and wealthier. I will not complete another survey for you if next year I find it is  again designed in a way that clearly deprioritizes patients for the privilege of the privileged.
